  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines (often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved)\n- Criminal forfeiture of assets\n\n2. Civil Penalties:\n- Additional monetary penalties\n- Asset seizure\n- Potential civil lawsuit from government\n\nSpecific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n- Whether it involves drug trafficking or other serious crimes\n- Prior criminal history\n\nThe primary federal statute covering money laundering is 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956, which defines different types of money laundering offenses and corresponding penalties.\n\nConsulting a qualified legal professional would provide the most accurate and current information specific to an individual case.",
